Yes — exactly.

The selected sales point should be sent to B2Boost during the **handoff exchange response**, and then B2Boost should store it in its **local security/session context**.

Flow:

```text
Arthur sales-point select
  → stores selectedSalesPointId in Arthur session
  → creates handoff code
  → redirects to B2Boost?code=...

B2Boost /post-login
  → calls Arthur /auth/handoff/exchange
  → receives selectedSalesPointId
  → creates B2Boost SecurityContext/session
```

Your exchange response should include:

```java
@Data
public class HandoffExchangeResponse {
    private String userId;
    private String username;
    private List<String> roles;
    private String appId;

    private String selectedSalesPointId;
    private String selectedOrgUnitId;
    private String selectedRelationshipType;
}
```

Then in B2Boost, after exchange:

```java
B2BoostUserPrincipal principal = new B2BoostUserPrincipal(
        response.getUserId(),
        response.getUsername(),
        response.getRoles(),
        response.getSelectedSalesPointId(),
        response.getSelectedOrgUnitId(),
        response.getSelectedRelationshipType()
);

Authentication authentication =
        new UsernamePasswordAuthenticationToken(
                principal,
                null,
                authorities
        );

SecurityContextHolder.getContext().setAuthentication(authentication);

request.getSession(true).setAttribute(
        HttpSessionSecurityContextRepository.SPRING_SECURITY_CONTEXT_KEY,
        SecurityContextHolder.getContext()
);
```

So yes: **salesPointId becomes part of B2Boost post-login security context**.

Do not make B2Boost trust a salesPointId from the browser directly. It should only trust the value returned by Arthur Core during handoff exchange.
